#!/usr/bin/env ssc
---
name: v2-string-split-limit-overload
description: String.split(delimiter, limit) — the two-arg overload — is completely unimplemented on v2; the one-arg split(delimiter) works fine
backends: [int]
---

# v2: `String.split(delimiter, limit)` (two-arg overload) is missing

**This exact gap crash-looped a real production instance of busi**
(2026-07-10) within minutes of a v1→v2 default flip reaching a live
server via a normal deploy. `identity.ssc`'s `readTsv()` parses a
real TSV sessions file via `line.split("\t", -1)` — the two-arg form,
delimiter + limit (`-1` = "keep trailing empty fields", the standard
idiom for TSV rows that may have a blank last column). On v2 this
raises an unhandled `RuntimeException: __method__: no dispatch for
.split` — no crash on `.split(delimiter)` alone (single arg), only on
the two-arg overload.

Every pre-flip verification (a full v1-vs-v2 A/B test suite covering
the money-loop end to end, a 30-route sweep over a seeded demo dataset,
and a real-browser e2e suite, all in busi's own repo) used a FRESH
data directory with no sessions file — so this line was never reached.
Only an instance with real prior login history has one, which is
exactly what production had and no test environment did. Repro reduced
to the single call below; v1 (INT) is correct, `--v2` raises the exact
same error text seen in the production crash log.

```scalascript
val s = "02e175cf-9668-4a5c-bea2-604a1581ac5e\tsergey.scherbina@gmail.com\tSergiy\towner,admin,manager"
val fields = s.split("\t", -1)
println(fields.length)
println(fields(1))
```
